# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: francis-birch-geophysicist
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] Previously at the University of California, Berkeley, he served as the 7th director of Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory from 2009 to 2016, as interim vice chancellor for research from 2016 to 2017, and as executive vice chancellor and provost from 2017 to 2021.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] His academic research focuses on nanomaterials, particularly nanocrystal fabrication for biomedical and renewable energy applications.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] Paul Alivisatos was born in Chicago, Illinois, where he lived until the age of 10, when his family moved to Athens, Greece.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] He returned to the United States to attend the University of Chicago in the late 1970s.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos received a Bachelor of Arts degree (with honors) with a major in chemistry from the University of Chicago in 1981 and a Ph.D. in physical chemistry from the University of California, Berkeley, in 1986.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] His doctoral advisor at Berkeley was Charles B.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] His doctoral thesis was titled *The photophysical properties of molecules near metal and semiconductor surfaces*.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] After receiving his doctorate, Alivisatos joined AT&T Bell Labs working with Louis E.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] Brus, and began research in the field of nanotechnology.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos returned to the University of California, Berkeley in 1988 as an assistant professor of chemistry.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] He was promoted to associate professor in 1993 and to full professor in 1995.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] In administrative roles, Alivisatos served as the 7th director of Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory from 2009 to 2016, as the university's interim vice chancellor for research from 2016 to 2017, and as executive vice chancellor and provost from 2017 to 2021.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] In August 2013, he was appointed as Samsung Distinguished Professor in Nanoscience and Nanotechnology Research.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] He was also the founding director of the Kavli Energy Nanosciences Institute (ENSI).
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos joined the Materials Sciences Division at Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory in 1991.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] He served as associate laboratory director for physical sciences from 2005 to 2007.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] In 2008, he became deputy director, and he stepped in as interim director after Steven Chu left to become United States Secretary of Energy under the first Obama administration.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] On November 19, 2009, Alivisatos was appointed 7th director of Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] He refocused the lab on renewable energy and climate research, oversaw new facilities, deepened ties to the national innovation ecosystem, and advanced collaborations that sped technology transfer across industries from autos to medicine.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] On March 23, 2015, he announced that he would step down from the directorship once a successor was named.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] On February 26, 2021, the Board of Trustees of the University of Chicago named Alivisatos as the incoming 14th president of the University of Chicago, with his term beginning on September 1, 2021.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] He succeeded Robert Zimmer, who served as the university president from July 2006 to August 2021.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] In addition to the office of the president, he was named the John D.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] MacArthur Distinguished Service Professor, chair of the Board of Governors of Argonne National Laboratory, and chair of the Board of Directors of Fermi Forward Discovery Group LLC, which operates the Fermi National Accelerator Laboratory.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] On September 24, 2025, the Board of Trustees of the University of Chicago extended Alivisatos's presidency through June 2030.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos is an internationally recognized authority on nano chemistry in the synthesis of semiconductor quantum dots and multi-shaped artificial nanostructures.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] Further, he is a world expert on the chemistry of nanoscale crystals; one of his papers (Science, 271: 933–937, 1996) has been cited over 13,800 times.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] He is also an expert on how these can be applied, for example as biological markers (e.g., Science, 281: 2013–16, 1998; a paper cited over 10,900 times).
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] In addition, his use of DNA in this area (DNA nanotechnology) has shown the surprising versatility of this molecule.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] He has used it to direct crystal growth and create new materials, as in Nature, 382: 609–11, 1996, and even to measure nanoscale distances (see Nature Nanotechnology, 1: 47–52, 2006).
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] In February 2011, Alivisatos was ranked fifth among the world's top 100 chemists for the period 2000–2010 in the list released by Thomson Reuters.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] He is widely recognized as being the first to demonstrate that semiconductor nanocrystals can be grown into complex two-dimensional shapes, as opposed to simple one-dimensional spheres.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos proved that controlling the growth of nanocrystals is the key to controlling both their size and shape.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] This achievement altered the nanoscience landscape and paved the way for a slew of new potential applications, including biomedical diagnostics, revolutionary photovoltaic cells, and LED materials.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] Given that a nanocrystal is virtually all surface and no interior, its properties can vary considerably as the crystal grows in size.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] Prior to Alivisatos's research, all non-metal nanocrystals were dot-shaped, meaning they were essentially one-dimensional.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] No techniques had been reported for making two-dimensional or rod-shaped semiconductor nanocrystals that would also be of uniform size.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] However, in a landmark paper that appeared in the March 2, 2000, issue of the journal Nature, Alivisatos reported on techniques used to select the size but vary the shapes of the nanocrystals produced.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] This was hailed as a major breakthrough in nanocrystal fabrication because rod-shaped semiconductor nanocrystals can be stacked to create nano-sized electronic devices.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos went on to use his techniques to create an entirely new generation of hybrid solar cells that combined nanotechnology with plastic electronics.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos is the founding scientist of Quantum Dot Corporation, a company that makes crystalline nanoscale tags that are used in the study of cell behavior.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] (Quantum Dot is now part of Life Technologies.) He also founded the nanotechnology company Nanosys, and Solexant, a photovoltaic start-up that has since restarted as Siva Power.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos is the founding editor of *Nano Letters*, a publication of the American Chemical Society.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] He formerly served on the Senior Editorial Board of *Science*.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] He has also served on the editorial advisory boards of*ACS Nano*, the *Journal of Physical Chemistry*, *Chemical Physics*, the *Journal of Chemical Physics*, and *Advanced Materials*.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] In addition to those listed above, Alivisatos has held fellowships with the American Association for the Advancement of Science, the American Physical Society (1996), and the American Chemical Society.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] He is a member of the National Academy of Sciences and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos is married to Nicole Alivisatos, a retired chemist, former editor of the journal Nano Letters, and daughter of the noted chemist, Gábor A.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] Abel Wolman was born to Louis and Rose Wachsman Wolman on June 10, 1892 in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] He was the fourth eldest child of Polish-Jewish immigrants.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] Wolman received his high school education from the Baltimore City College in 1909.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] Following his high school education, Wolman received his Bachelor of Arts in 1913 as a pre-med major.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] Although Wolman was interested in becoming a doctor, his mother's insistence on studying engineering led him to pursue a degree in engineering.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] He then went on to complete a Bachelor of Science in Engineering at the Johns Hopkins University, graduating in 1915 as the fourth person to receive a degree at the newly-established Whiting School of Engineering.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] Although Wolman did not complete a doctorate degree, his work in the field of sanitary engineering led to him being awarded an honorary Doctor of Engineering in 1937.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] Wolman was also awarded a Doctor of Humane Letters from the Maryland Institute College of Arts and a Doctor of Law by the Johns Hopkins University in 1969.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] Wolman served an extensive career in sanitary engineering, working in both environmental and public health services as well as in academics.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] In 1914, he started his long career in public health as an assistant engineer working for the United States Public Health Service.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] In 1922, Wolman became the Chief Engineer of the Maryland State Department of Health, where he served for 18 years until 1939.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] While working in the public health sector, Wolman conducted research related to sanitation and public health.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] He is best known for his 1919 contribution, with chemist Linn Enslow, in the standardization of chlorinating Baltimore's drinking-water supply.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] His efforts there helped develop the plan for Baltimore's water supply so thoroughly and effectively that it remains well-provided for growth through the 21st century.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] His work also benefited water systems in New York, Detroit and Columbus, Ohio.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] At that same time, he served as the Department of Sanitary Engineering's chairman until his official retirement in 1962.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] During his time as a sanitary engineering lecturer, he was asked to lecture at many prestigious universities, including Harvard University, Princeton University, University of Southern California, and University of Chicago.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] He was appointed Professor Emeritus in 1962, but had no desire to retire from professional life, so he continued his teaching and research in addition to serving as a consultant to the many governments and municipalities that requested his advice and assistance.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] Supplementing his professional life, Wolman also held many important positions in the committees of professional societies and journal publications.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] In 1916, he joined the American Public Health Association as an associate editor of the organization's monthly publication, *American Journal of Public Health,* where he eventually became the editor in 1955 until 1957.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] Within the American Public Health Association, Wolman served as Chairman of the Public Health Engineering Section and Chairman of the Committee on Research and Standards.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] Through their marriage, Wolman had one son, named Markley (M.) Gordon Wolman.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] Maintaining a lively and witty personality, Wolman was favorable amongst many of the students he interacted with as a professor.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] From colleagues and family members that knew Wolman well, he has been described as being very well-organized and always perceptive towards his problems and analyses related to work.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] Wolman died at his home in Baltimore, Maryland on February 22, 1989, aged 96 years old.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] In collaboration with Linn Enslow, Wolman wanted to standardize a chlorination method to purify municipal water supplies.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] At the time, the purification of water with chlorine was known and employed in cities, but the problem that Wolman and Enslow highlighted in this publication was that the dosage of chlorine used by cities were unreliable and unscientific.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] As a result, municipal water supplies were often incorrectly purified, leading to failures in performance marked by diseases.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] Wolman and Enslow began their experiment by describing their observations on the rate of chlorine absorption in different water samples that varied in bacteria, color, turbidity, oxidizable compounds, and other purity factors.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] In "The Metabolism of Cities", Wolman highlighted three major "metabolic" problems that plagued major cities in the United States and offered his insight on the reality of those problems and possible solutions.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] He defined the metabolic requirements of a city as all materials and commodities needed to sustain its population, including all processes related to the proper removal and disposal of waste products produced in daily life.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] However, he pointed out that many major US cities share three metabolic problems: (1) lack of an adequate water supply, (2) ineffective disposal of sewage, and (3) poor control of air pollution.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] Throughout most of the paper, Wolman provided relevant statistics and figures to underscore the proposed metabolic problems and analyzed historical municipal proposals designed to alleviate those metabolic problems.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] He concluded the article on a somewhat optimistic note, mentioning that the future of water sanitation, sewage disposal, and eliminating air pollutants is hopeful.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] However, in order to reach that future, Wolman called for immediate action and planning of policies and programs needed to combat the three metabolic problems.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] Since the publication of this paper, there have been many studies performed to develop viable solutions to tackle the water shortages, waste disposal, and air pollution issues proposed by Wolman.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] For example, in 1999, civil and environmental engineers at the University of California, Berkeley published a research paper that confirmed the presence of water shortages in the United States and advocated for cities to take water recycling and reuse measures.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] For his efforts in public health practices and engineering skills on a local and global level, Wolman was granted multiple awards.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] In 1948, Wolman was awarded the Sedgwick Memorial Medal by the American Public Health Association for his contributions in the field of public health.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] In 1960, he was awarded the Albert Lasker Special Award in Public Health, which is an award "for outstanding contributions in research related to diseases which are the main causes of death and disability and for distinguished service in the field of public health administration.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] In 1967, Wolman was awarded the William Procter Prize for Scientific Achievement for his contributions in the field of science.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] In 1968, Wolman was awarded the first Lewis L.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] In 1973, Wolman was awarded the Milton Stover Eisenhower Medal.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] In 1974, Wolman was awarded the National Medal of Science.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] In 1976, Wolman was awarded the Tyler Prize for Environmental Achievement and the Ben Gurion Award.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] Both in 1973 and 1977, Wolman was awarded the American Water Works Association Award.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] In 1986, Wolman was awarded the Robert E.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] Horton Medal and the John Wesley Powell Award.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] Finally, in 1999, The Baltimore Sun named Wolman "Marylander of the Century".
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] Following the death of Wolman, multiple tributes were created in his honor.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] For individuals that work in the water industry, the American Water Works Association annually presents the Abel Wolman Award of Excellence since 1985.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] In May 1966, the Johns Hopkins University named a newly acquired dormitory Wolman Hall, which continues to house first year students.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/abel-wolman] In 1986, the City of Baltimore renamed its public works building to the Abel Wolman Municipal Building, honoring his years of service to the city.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] Knopf was a member of the National Academy of Sciences and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] He served as president of the Geological Society of America in 1944 and received its Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] His second wife, Eleanora Knopf, was a notable geologist and frequent collaborator.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] Knopf was born December 2, 1882, in San Francisco, California, to German American immigrants.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] He grew up with his family on a ranch near Woodside, California.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] Knopf entered the University of California, Berkeley, where he became a student of petrology under Andrew Lawson.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] He earned a Bachelor of Science degree in mining geology in 1904 and a Master of Science degree in 1905.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] That same year he spent the first of six summers surveying the mineral deposits of Alaska for the United States Geological Survey (USGS).
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] In 1906 he moved to Washington, D.C., to work for the USGS full-time.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] The Alaskan Division, of which Knopf was one of about a dozen members, was considered the best geologic group in the USGS at that time.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] Knopf's work on tin deposits in the Seward Peninsula became the basis of the dissertation for his Ph.D., which he received from Berkeley in 1909.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] In Alaska he also discovered the minerals hulsite and paigeite.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] In 1911 Knopf was promoted from assistant geologist to geologist.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] Over the next nine years he undertook a series of field projects for the USGS, beginning with the mining district in Montana that includes the Boulder Batholith and continuing to other western states including Nevada and California.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] In the latter state he surveyed the Gold Country.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] After discovering that universities on the eastern seaboard were paying about double the USGS salaries, Knopf left the USGS for a teaching position, and a number of his colleagues followed suit.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale University in January 1920.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] He encouraged students to work with the USGS as he had done; this helped mitigate the agency's brain drain following the departures.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale as an associate professor but was promoted to full professor in 1923.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] He was named the Silliman Professor of Geology in 1937 and a Sterling Professor in 1938.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] He was director of graduate studies from 1933 until his retirement from Yale in 1951.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] Upon retiring he returned to his native Woodside, California, settling not far from his family's old ranch.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] There he accepted a visiting appointment at the Stanford University School of Earth Sciences, where he remained until his death in 1966.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] Knopf's field work continued through his Yale and Stanford appointments, again with a focus on western states.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] He continued his work in the Boulder Batholith and investigated intrusive igneous rock bodies in the Spanish Peaks in Colorado.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] He also contributed to the emerging field of geochronology, putting lower bounds of 2 billion years and later 4.5 billion years on the age of the Earth.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] Knopf was elected to the National Academy of Sciences in 1931.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] He was also a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and of the Geological Society of America.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] He was president of the Geological Society of America in 1944, and he received the Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] In 1937 he was vice president of the Society of Economic Geologists.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] In 1908 Knopf married Agnes Burchard Dillon.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] They had three daughters and one son, though one of the daughters died in infancy.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] Agnes died in 1918 in that year's flu pandemic.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] In June 1920, Knopf married fellow USGS geologist Eleanora Frances Bliss, who as Eleanora Knopf became a frequent collaborator and travel companion.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] When Adolph moved to Yale, which did not then hire women, Eleanora worked out of Adolph's office, teaching private classes and still accepting USGS assignments.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] When they moved to California, Stanford hired her as a research associate.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] Knopf died November 23, 1966, in Palo Alto, California.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] In his will he endowed a chaired professorship at Yale.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] The sitting Adolph Knopf Professor of Petrology is Shun-ichiro Karato.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] Adolph and Eleanora Knopf also endowed a graduate fellowship in petrology at Stanford.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/adolph-knopf] Mount Adolph Knopf in Juneau Borough, Alaska is named after him.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] The "American Ambulance" of 1914 took over the premises of the unfinished Lycée Pasteur in the suburb of Neuilly-sur-Seine—and was run by the nearby American Hospital of Paris.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] The volunteer drivers of 1914 found themselves behind the wheels of motorized, not horse-driven, vehicles: Model-Ts, purchased from the nearby Ford plant in Levallois-Perret.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] In the fall of 1914, when the war front moved away from Paris, the American Ambulance set up an outpost in Juilly and sent out detached units of volunteer drivers to serve informally with the British and Belgian armies in the north.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Piatt Andrew, was appointed "Inspector of Ambulances" by Robert Bacon, head of the American Ambulance and one of Andrew's colleagues from the Taft Administration.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] The newly appointed inspector toured the ambulance sections of Northern France and learned that the American volunteers were bored with so-called "jitney work," transporting wounded soldiers from railheads to hospitals far back from the front lines.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] French army policy prohibited foreign nationals from traveling into battle zones.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] In March 1915, Andrew met with Captain Aimé Doumenc, head of the French Army Automobile Service and pleaded his case for the American volunteers.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] They desired above all, he said, "to pick up the wounded from the front lines..., to look danger squarely in the face; in a word, to mingle with the soldiers of France and to share their fate!" Doumenc agreed to give Andrew a trial.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] The success of Section Z was immediate and overwhelming, and by April 15, 1915, the French created American Ambulance Field Service operating under French Army command.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Sections of about 30 drivers each were assigned to individual French Army divisions.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] The volunteer drivers at first joined for six months at a time; some received acting officer uniforms and ranks to work with the French officers that commanded the units.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] This marked the formal beginning of American Ambulance Field Service, three units of which made their mark during battles in northern France, the Champagne, Verdun and the Vosges.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] By the summer of 1916, the Field Service severed its ties with the American Ambulance and moved its operations from cramped quarters in Neuilly to Paris, onto the spacious grounds of the Delessert château at 21 rue Raynouard in the Passy area of Paris.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] There, it grew rapidly over the next year, continuing to provide "sanitary sections" to the French Army, while also serving as a recruitment source of combat pilots for the newly formed Escadrille Lafayette, one of whose prime movers, Edmund L.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Gros, was the Field Service's in-house physician.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] By 1917 the Field Service had 33 ambulance sections with about 1200 volunteers total.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] When the United States entered the war in April 1917, the French Army successfully appealed to the Field Service for drivers for its military transport sections.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Using excess ambulance volunteers that agreed to enlist in the French Army, the service established 14 transportation combat units with 800 drivers carrying ammunition and supplies.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] No longer limited to medical transport, the organization renamed itself the "American Field Service", thus establishing today's well-known acronym, "AFS".
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] While American media described the ambulance and transport units as easy duty, many volunteered for AFS to join the fighting as fast as possible.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Before the AFS was absorbed into the much larger, federalized U.S.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Army Ambulance Service in autumn 1917 (many transport drivers joining the Motor Transport Corps), it had numbered more than 2500 volunteers, including some 800 drivers of French military transport trucks.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] It had actively recruited its drivers from the campuses of American colleges and universities, promoting morale by creating units with volunteers from the same schools.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] All financed their own uniforms and transportation to France where they worked under the same conditions as French ambulance drivers—with the same pay—and often found themselves serving under extremely dangerous missions on the Front.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] By the end of the war, some 127 men who had served with the AFS had been killed and a notable number of individuals and units had earned the Croix de Guerre and the Médaille de Guerre for their heroic actions as drivers.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Other volunteer ambulance corps served the French Army as "foreign sanitary sections" during World War I.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] The first was Henry Harjes’’ "Formation" units under the American Red Cross, followed by Richard Norton's American Volunteer Motor-Ambulance Corps, organized in London under the St.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] John's Ambulance (the British Red Cross).
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Later, both would merge —under the American Red Cross—as the "Norton-Harjes".
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] In the summer and fall of 1917, when all the volunteer ambulance services were invited to join the new U.S.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Army Ambulance Service, Norton's units simply disbanded, while Harjes’, under the American Red Cross, moved into Italy where they would subsequently serve under the USAAS.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Once the Americans entered the war, many drivers joined combat units, both French and American, serving as officers in a variety of assignments, notably in air force and artillery units.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] The young AFS drivers came from "prominent families in the States," and had attended, or were still attending, one of almost a hundred prominent colleges or universities around the country.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Also represented were a smaller group from America's professional class: doctors, lawyers, architects, painters, brokers, businessmen, poets and writers.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] This literate group produced many letters, diaries, journals, and even poetry.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] The AFS collected many of these writings into *Friends of France*, published in 1916.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] The Service used this volume to recruit more volunteers to the "gloriously exciting and grandly humanitarian" work of an ambulancier on the Western Front.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Also published in 1916, *Ambulance Number 10*, by Leslie Buswell, was composed of the author's letters back to the States.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Buswell went on to assist Henry Sleeper in the AFS's recruiting and fundraising offices in Boston.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Other literary "ambulanciers" brought their letters and journals and memoirs to American publishers in the coming years.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] William Yorke Stevenson produced *To The Front in a Flivver* in 1917, stayed on in France after militarization, and composed *From "Poilu" to "Yank"* in 1918.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Robert Imbrie published *Behind the Wheel of a War Ambulance* in 1918, as did Julien Bryan with *Ambulance 464: Encore des Blesses*.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] The AFS recruits who joined the Service in late spring 1917, after Congress's declaration of war, were greeted by Piatt Andrew with a request: Would they forego ambulance driving for trucking supplies to the front?
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Eight hundred AFS recruits joined the camion service, including John Kautz, who published *Trucking to the Trenches* in 1918.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] After the war the Field Service produced three hefty volumes of writings from numerous AFS alumni, including excerpts from the previously published books above.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Following the Great War, the AFS became sponsors for the French Fellowships—graduate student scholarships for study in France and in the US—which were ultimately administered by the Institute of International Education and were precedents for the Fulbright Foundation exchanges.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] AFS also created an association for its veterans, publishing a bulletin, organizing reunions and contributing a wing to house its memorabilia at the Museum of Franco-American Cooperation in Blérancourt, France.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] When World War II broke out, AFS reorganized its ambulance service, sending units first to France and then to the British Armies in North Africa, Italy, India-Burma and with the Free French for the final drive from southern France to Germany.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] 2,196 men served in the AFS during World War II.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Twenty-five were sons of World War I AFS drivers.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] While US Army officers were paid $75 to $105 monthly, AFS drivers as unpaid volunteers paid at least $390 each year to serve; basic equipment cost $150, and at least $20 each month for other expenses.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Families deposited money at AFS headquarters, and volunteers withdrew funds from AFS cashers in the field.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] AFS encouraged sponsorship of drivers, and in August 1943 began providing a $20 monthly living allowance.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] AFS favored the Dodge WC54 4x4 ambulance; each cost $2000, usually paid by donation.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Seventy AFS Ambulance Drivers assisted the efforts to liberate the Bergen-Belsen concentration camp in April and May 1945.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] In September 1946, Stephen Galatti, president of AFS, established the American Field Service International Scholarships.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] During the 1947–48 school year, the first students came from ten countries including Czechoslovakia, Estonia, France, Great Britain, Greece, Hungary, the Netherlands, New Zealand, Norway and Syria.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Students participating had to be nominated by their teachers.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] As of 2023, there are over 60 AFS organizations worldwide serving over 80 different countries, providing exchange opportunities for over 13,000 students and teachers annually.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] AFS is one of the largest volunteer-based organizations of its kind in the world with more than 50,000 volunteers worldwide and more than 5,000 in the U.S.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Tens of thousands of volunteers and a small staff make the AFS program happen worldwide.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] AFS volunteers are both young and old, busy professionals and retirees, and students and teachers.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] AFS provides development and training opportunities for volunteers.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] AFS volunteers help in many areas including facilitating the AFS mission in the local community and schools by finding and interviewing students and families.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Further involvement includes serving as a contact person for an AFS student, organizing fund raising events, and arranging activities for AFS students.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] As a volunteer-driven organization, AFS depends on donations of time to implement and monitor the delivery of programs.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] In 2025, AFS was designated as an undesirable organization in Russia.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] EFIL does not engage in active student exchanges between countries.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Instead, it supports member organizations in the field of intercultural learning.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] The European Union and the Council of Europe are the organization's core Partners for fundraising, policy-setting and sharing.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] The main activities include networking and advocacy, training and seminars for volunteers and staff, establishing new partner countries in Europe, and coordinating Europe-wide projects.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] It is an important European Youth organization and an active member of the European Youth Forum.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] AFS is an international, voluntary, non-governmental, non-profit organization that provides intercultural learning opportunities to help people develop the knowledge, skills and understanding needed to create a more just and peaceful world.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] (a.k.a., AFS-USA) is the AFS partner organization in the United States and is a registered 501 (c) (3).
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Approximately 500 participants go abroad with AFS-USA annually.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Over 1,000 international AFS students from other countries are hosted in the U.S. annually.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] AFS-USA is supported by a volunteer base of over 2,500.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Study abroad programs range from two week group trips, to traditional year-long exchanges.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Students on traditional exchanges live in volunteer host families, and study at a local high school.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Other programs include community service, university classes, or language classes.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Public Diplomacy Initiatives at AFS-USA offer support for international students to study in the United States and for U.S. students to study abroad via full funded scholarships by grant-making foundations or by the Educational and Cultural Affairs Bureau of the U.S.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] The Congress Bundestag Youth Exchange Program (CBYX) was launched in 1983 by the U.S.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] AFS currently provides 50 merit-based, full scholarships for U.S. students and 60 scholarships for German participants.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] In Germany it is called the "Parlamentarisches Patenschafts Programm" (PPP) and over the years the German authorities have made many efforts to present this as their "own program".
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Not only AFS Germany but all competitors are more or less behind-the-scene service providers so people may not recognized who is doing this program in Germany.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] AFS hosts German CBYX students throughout the US, and administers the scholarship for US students located in the Northeast.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] The National Security Language Initiative for Youth (NSLI-Y) program is part of a broader government-wide presidential initiative that prepares American citizens to be leaders in a global world.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] NSLI-Y encourages a lifetime of language study and cultural understanding by providing more than 600 fully funded scholarships to American high school students.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] The Future Leaders Exchange (FLEX) program originated in the FREEDOM Support Act, which was sponsored by U.S.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Senator Bill Bradley and was passed by Congress in 1992.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] FLEX provides full merit-based scholarships to students from the countries of the former Soviet Union.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Kennedy-Lugar Youth Exchange and Study (YES) was initiated by The Department of State in the aftermath of Sept.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] It aims to build bridges of understanding between Americans and people in countries with significant Muslim populations.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Students from over 40 countries come to the US for academic year programs.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Countries that formerly participated include Algeria, Ethiopia, Yemen, Iraq, Oman, Qatar, and Syria.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Former host countries include Egypt, Mali, Oman, Philippines, and South Africa.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/afs-intercultural-programs] Scholarships awarded by the AFS were formerly known as American Field Scholarships.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] A 2002 survey ranked Bandura as the fourth most frequently cited psychologist of all time, behind B.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Skinner, Sigmund Freud, and Jean Piaget.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] In April 2025, Bandura became the first psychologist with more than a million Google Scholar citations.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] During his lifetime, Bandura was widely described as the greatest living psychologist, and as one of the most influential psychologists of all time.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Bandura was born in Mundare, Alberta, an open town of roughly 400 inhabitants, as the youngest of six children.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] The limitations of education in his remote town caused Bandura to become independent and self-motivated in terms of learning, and the primarily-developed traits proved helpful later in his career.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Bandura was of Polish and Ukrainian descent; his father was from Kraków, Poland, while his mother was from Ukraine.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Bandura's parents were a key influence in encouraging him to seek ventures out of the small hamlet they resided in.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] The summer after finishing high school, Bandura worked in the Yukon to protect the Alaska Highway against sinking.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Bandura later credited his work in the northern tundra as the origin of his interest in human psychopathology.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] His experience in the Yukon, where he was exposed to a subculture of drinking and gambling, helped broaden his perspective and scope of views on life.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Bandura arrived in the United States in 1949 and was naturalized in 1956.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] He married Virginia Varns (1921–2011) in 1952, and they raised two daughters, Carol and Mary.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Bandura took psychology courses in college and became passionate about the subject.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] He graduated after three years in 1949 with a B.A. from the University of British Columbia, winning the Bolocan Award in psychology, and then moved to the then-epicenter of psychology, the University of Iowa, from where he obtained his M.A. in 1951 and Ph.D. in clinical psychology in 1952.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Arthur Benton was his academic adviser at Iowa, giving Bandura a direct academic descent from William James, while Clark Hull and Kenneth Spence were influential collaborators.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] During his Iowa years, Bandura came to support a style of psychology that sought to investigate psychological phenomena through repeatable, experimental testing.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] His inclusion of such mental phenomena as imagery and representation, and his concept of reciprocal determinism, which postulated a relationship of mutual influence between an agent and its environment, marked a radical departure from the dominant behaviorism of the time.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Upon graduation, he completed his postdoctoral internship at the Wichita Guidance Center.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] The following year, 1953, he accepted a teaching position at Stanford University, which he held until he became professor emeritus in 2010.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] In 1974, he was elected president of the American Psychological Association (APA), the world's largest association of psychologists.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Bandura would later state the only reason he agreed to be in the running for the APA election was because he wanted his 15 minutes of fame without any intentions of being elected.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Bandura was initially influenced by Robert Sears' work on familial antecedents of social behavior and identificatory learning and gave up his research of the psychoanalytic theory.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] He directed his initial research to the role of social modeling in human motivation, thought, and action.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] In collaboration with Richard Walters, his first doctoral student, he engaged in studies of social learning and aggression.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Their joint efforts illustrated the critical role of modeling in human behavior and led to a program of research into the determinants and mechanisms of observational learning.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] The initial phase of Bandura's research analyzed the foundations of human learning and the willingness of children and adults to imitate behavior that they observed in other people, particularly the emotion of aggression.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] The research indicated models as an important means for learning new behaviors and for achieving behavioral change in an institutional setting.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Social learning theory posits three regulatory systems that control human behavior.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Response and feedback influences have an important function.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Following a response to a stimulus, the reinforcements, either by experience or by observation, will determine future occurrences of the behavior.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Cognitive functions are important in social learning.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] For example, for aggressive behavior to occur, some people are readily angered by the sight or the thought of persons with whom they had hostile encounters, and that aggression-inducing memory is learned.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Social learning theory became one of the theoretical frameworks for Entertainment-Education, a method of creating socially beneficial entertainment pioneered by Miguel Sabido.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Bandura and Sabido went on to forge a close relationship and further refine the theory and practice.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] His research with Walters led to his first book, *Adolescent Aggression* (1959), followed by *Social Learning and Personality Development* (1963), and *Aggression: A Social Learning Analysis* (1973).
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] During a period dominated by behaviorism in the mold of B.F.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Skinner, Bandura believed the sole behavioral modifiers of reward and punishment in classical and operant conditioning were inadequate as a framework, and that many human behaviors were learned from other humans.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Bandura began to analyze the means of treating unduly aggressive children by identifying sources of violence in their lives.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Initial research in the area had begun in the 1940s under Neal Miller and John Dollard; his continued work in this line eventually culminated in the Bobo doll experiment, which led to his 1977 treatise, *Social Learning Theory*.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Many of his innovations came from his focus on empirical investigation and reproducible investigation, contrary to Sigmund Freud's popular theories of psychoanalysis.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] In 1974, Stanford University awarded him an endowed chair and he became David Starr Jordan Professor of Social Science in Psychology.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] In 1961, Bandura conducted a controversial experiment known as the Bobo doll experiment, which was designed to show that similar behaviors were learned by individuals shaping their own behavior after the actions of models.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] The experiment emphasized how young individuals are influenced by the acts of adults.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] When the adults were praised for their aggressive behavior, the children were more likely to keep on hitting the doll.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] However, when the adults were punished, they consequently stopped hitting the doll as well.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Bandura's results from the experiment were widely credited with helping shift the focus in academic psychology from pure behaviorism to cognitive psychology.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] By the mid-1980s, Bandura's research had taken a more holistic bent, and his analysis tended toward giving a more comprehensive overview of human cognition in the context of social learning.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] The theory he expanded from social learning theory soon became known as social cognitive theory.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] The foundation of Bandura's social learning theory is the idea that people may learn by seeing and copying the observable behaviors of others.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] As an alternative to the earlier work of colleague psychologist B.F.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Skinner, who was well known for advocating the behaviorist theory, psychologists Bandura and Sears presented the social learning hypothesis.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] In 1986, Bandura published *Social Foundations of Thought and Action: A Social Cognitive Theory*, in which he re-conceptualized individuals as self-organizing, proactive, self-reflecting, and self-regulating, in opposition to the orthodox conception of humans as governed by external forces.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] He advanced concepts of triadic reciprocal causation, which determined the connections between human behavior, environmental factors, and personal factors such as cognitive, affective, and biological events, and of reciprocal determinism, governing the causal relations between such factors.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Bandura's emphasis on the capacity of agents to self-organize and self-regulate would eventually give rise to his later work on self-efficacy.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] While investigating the processes by which modeling alleviates phobic disorders in snake-phobics, he found that self-efficacy beliefs (which the phobic individuals had in their own capabilities to alleviate their phobia) mediated changes in behavior and in fear-arousal.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] He launched a major program of research examining the influential role of self-referent thought in psychological functioning.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Although he continued to explore and write on theoretical problems relating to myriad topics, from the late 1970s, he devoted much attention to exploring the role of self-efficacy beliefs in human functioning.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] In 1986, he published *Social Foundations of Thought and Action: A Social Cognitive Theory*, a book in which he offered a social cognitive theory of human functioning that accords a central role to cognitive, vicarious, self-regulatory, and self-reflective processes in human adaptation and change.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] This theory has roots in an agentic perspective that views people as self-organizing, proactive, self-reflecting, and self-regulating, not just as reactive organisms shaped by environmental forces or driven by inner impulses.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] His book, *Self-Efficacy: The Exercise of Control* was published in 1997.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] The application of Bandura's self-efficacy research did not end with phobia-mediation, however, but extended into healthcare, particularly in the management of addictive behaviors such as smoking and smoking cessation.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] In these interventions, an individual's confidence in their ability to resist cravings and high-risk triggers was found to be a strong predictor of relapse.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Successful, long-term maintenance of cessation and positive alterations in usage were consistently associated with higher self-efficacy, suggesting that emphasizing and enhancing one's confidence could reduce rates of relapse.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] These findings validate Bandura's theory and demonstrate ways in which targeting self-efficacy has predicted treatment outcomes in addictive behaviors.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Bandura's social cognitive theories have been applied to education as well, mainly focusing on self-efficacy, self-regulation, observational learning, and reciprocal determinism.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Bandura's research showed that high perceived self-efficacy led teachers and students to set higher goals, and it increased the likelihood that they would dedicate themselves to those goals.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] In an educational setting, self-efficacy refers to a student or teacher's confidence to participate in certain actions that will help them achieve distinct goals.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] Bandura died at his home in Stanford, on July 26, 2021, from congestive heart failure, at the age of 95.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] He was elected a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1980.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] He received the Award for Distinguished Scientific Contributions from the American Psychological Association (APA) in 1980 for pioneering the research in the field of self-regulated learning.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] In 1999, he received the Thorndike Award for Distinguished Contributions of Psychology to Education from the APA, and in 2001, he received the Lifetime Achievement Award from the Association for the Advancement of Behavior Therapy.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] In 2008, he received the University of Louisville Grawemeyer Award for contributions to psychology.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] In 2014, he was made an Officer of the Order of Canada "for his foundational contributions to social psychology, notably for uncovering the influence of observation on human learning and aggression".
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-bandura] In 2016, he was awarded the National Medal of Science by president Barack Obama.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-overhauser] Born in San Diego, California, Overhauser attended high school in San Francisco at Lick-Wilmerding High School and began his undergraduate work at the University of California, Berkeley in 1942.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-overhauser] He interrupted his studies during World War II for a two-year stint in the U.S.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-overhauser] Navy Reserve, then returned to Berkeley to complete his education.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-overhauser] Overhauser received a Bachelor of Arts with major in physics and mathematics in 1948 and a Doctor of Philosophy in 1952 in physics, both from the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-overhauser] His doctoral advisor was Charles Kittel.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-overhauser] From 1951 to 1953, he was a post-doctoral researcher at the University of Illinois, where he developed his highly cited theory on the transfer of spin polarization; once the theory had been confirmed and demonstrated by other scientists, it became known as the Overhauser effect.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-overhauser] He was on the faculty at Cornell University from 1953 to 1958, and then left to join the research staff at Ford Motor Company.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-overhauser] Overhauser remained at Ford until 1973, when he joined the faculty at Purdue University.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-overhauser] He remained at Purdue as the Stuart Distinguished Professor of Physics for the rest of his career.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-overhauser] Overhauser died in 2011 in West Lafayette, Indiana.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] Abram Saperstejn was born in Białystok, Russian Empire (before and since 1918 in Poland), to Polish-Jewish parents, Jacob Saperstejn and Tillie Krugman.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] In 1921, he emigrated with his family on the SS *Lapland* which sailed from Antwerp to the Port of New York.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] In 1930, he became a naturalized citizen of the United States and changed his name to Albert Bruce Sabin.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] He graduated from high school in Paterson, New Jersey.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] Sabin began university in a dentistry program, but was interested in virology and changed majors.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] He received a bachelor's degree in science in 1928 and a medical degree in 1931 from New York University.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] In 1983, Sabin developed calcification of the cervical spine, which caused paralysis and intense pain.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] Sabin revealed in a television interview that the experience had made him decide to spend the rest of his life working on alleviating pain.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] This condition was successfully treated by surgery conducted at Johns Hopkins Hospital in 1992 when Sabin was 86.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] A year later, Sabin died in Washington, D.C., from heart failure.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] Sabin trained in internal medicine, pathology, and surgery at Bellevue Hospital in New York City from 1931 to 1933.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] In 1934, he conducted research at The Lister Institute for Preventive Medicine in England, then joined the Rockefeller Institute for Medical Research (now Rockefeller University).
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] During this time, he developed an intense interest in research, especially in the area of infectious diseases.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] In 1939, he moved to Cincinnati Children's Hospital in Cincinnati, Ohio.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] During World War II, he was a lieutenant colonel in the U.S.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] Army Medical Corps and helped develop a vaccine against Japanese encephalitis.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] Maintaining his association with Children's Hospital, by 1946, he had also become the head of Pediatric Research at the University of Cincinnati.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] At Cincinnati's Children's Hospital, Sabin supervised the fellowship of Robert M.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] Chanock, whom he called his "star scientific son".
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] In 1969–72, he lived in Israel, serving as president of Weizmann Institute of Science in Rehovot.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] After his return to the United States, he worked (1974–82) as a research professor at the Medical University of South Carolina.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] He later moved to the Washington, D.C., area, where he was a resident scholar at the John E.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] Fogarty International Center on the NIH campus in Bethesda, Maryland.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] With the menace of polio growing, Sabin and other researchers, most notably Jonas Salk in Pittsburgh and Hilary Koprowski and H.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] Cox in New York City and Philadelphia, respectively, sought a vaccine to prevent or mitigate the illness.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] This was complicated because there were multiple strains of the disease.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] In 1951, the National Foundation for Infantile Paralysis's typing program confirmed the existence of three main serotypes of poliovirus, since known as type 1, type 2, and type 3.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] Salk developed an inactivated poliovirus vaccine (IPV), a "dead" vaccine given by injection, which was released for use in 1955.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] It was effective in preventing most of the complications of polio, but did not prevent the initial intestinal infection.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] By carrying out autopsies of polio victims, Sabin was able to demonstrate that the poliovirus multiplied and attacked the intestines before it moved to the central nervous system.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] This also suggested that polio virus could be grown in other tissues besides embryonic brain tissue, leading to easier and cheaper methods of vaccine development.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] John Enders, Thomas Huckle Weller, and Frederick Robbins would successfully grow poliovirus in laboratory cultures of non-nerve tissue in 1949, an achievement that earned them the 1954 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] Sabin developed an oral vaccine based on mutant strains of polio virus that seemed to stimulate antibody production but not to cause paralysis.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] Recipients of his live attenuated oral vaccine included himself, family, and colleagues.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] Sabin's first clinical trials were carried out at the Chillicothe Ohio Reformatory in late 1954.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] From 1956–1960, he worked with Russian colleagues to perfect the oral vaccine and prove its extraordinary effectiveness and safety.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] The Sabin vaccine worked in the intestines to block the poliovirus from entering the bloodstream.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] Between 1955 and 1961, the oral vaccine was tested on at least 100 million people in the USSR, parts of Eastern Europe, Singapore, Mexico, and the Netherlands.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] The first industrial production and mass use of oral poliovirus vaccine (OPV) from Sabin strains was organized by Soviet scientist Mikhail Chumakov.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] This provided the critical impetus for allowing large-scale clinical trials of OPV in the United States in April 1960 on 180,000 Cincinnati school children.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] The mass immunization techniques that Sabin pioneered with his associates effectively eradicated polio in Cincinnati.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] Against considerable opposition from the March of Dimes Foundation, which supported use of Salk's relatively effective killed vaccine, Sabin prevailed on the Public Health Service (PHS) to license his three strains of vaccine.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] While the PHS stalled, the USSR sent millions of doses of the oral vaccine to places with polio epidemics, such as Japan.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] Sabin's first oral poliovirus vaccine (OPV), for use against type 1 polioviruses, was licensed in the United States in 1961.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] His vaccines for type 2 and type 3 polioviruses were licensed in 1962.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] At first, the monovalent poliovirus vaccines were administered together by being put on a sugar cube, because the oral polio vaccine had a bitter, salty taste (inspiring Robert B.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] Sherman's lyrics to *A Spoonful of Sugar (Helps the Medicine Go Down)* for the 1964 film *Mary Poppins*).
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] In 1964, a single trivalent OPV containing all three viral serotypes was approved.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] Sabin's oral vaccine was easier to give than the earlier vaccine developed by Salk in 1954, and its effects lasted longer.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] The Sabin vaccine became the predominant method of vaccination against polio in the United States for the next three decades.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] It broke the chain of transmission of the virus and allowed for the possibility that polio might one day be eradicated.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] Sabin also developed vaccines against other viral diseases, including encephalitis and dengue.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] In addition, he investigated possible links between viruses and some forms of cancer.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] Sabin refused to patent his vaccine, waiving commercial exploitation by pharmaceutical industries, so that the low price would guarantee a more extensive spread of the treatment.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] From the development of his vaccine Sabin did not gain a penny, and continued to live on his salary as a professor.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] The Sabin Vaccine Institute was founded in 1993 to continue the work of developing and promoting vaccines.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] To commemorate Sabin's pioneering work, the institute annually awards the Albert B.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/albert-sabin] Sabin Gold Medal in recognition of work in the field of vaccinology or a complementary field.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] During World War II, Birch participated in the Manhattan Project, working on the design and development of the gun-type nuclear weapon known as Little Boy.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] He oversaw its manufacture, and went to Tinian to supervise its assembly and loading into *Enola Gay*, the Boeing B-29 Superfortress tasked with dropping the bomb.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] A graduate of Harvard University, Birch began working on geophysics as a research assistant.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] He subsequently spent his entire career at Harvard working in the field, becoming an associate professor of geology in 1943, a professor in 1946, and Sturgis Hooper Professor of Geology in 1949, and professor emeritus in 1974.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] He developed what is now known as the Birch-Murnaghan equation of state in 1947.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] In 1952 he demonstrated that Earth's mantle is chiefly composed of silicate minerals, with an inner and outer core of molten iron.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] In two 1961 papers on compressional wave velocities, he established what is now called Birch's law.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] Birch was born in Washington, D.C., on August 22, 1903, the son of George Albert Birch, who was involved in banking and real estate, and Mary Hemmick Birch, a church choir singer and soloist at St.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] He had three younger brothers: David, who became a banker; John, who became a diplomat; and Robert, who became a songwriter.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] He was educated at Washington, D.C., schools, and Western High School, where he joined the High School Cadets in 1916.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] In 1920 Birch entered Harvard University on a scholarship.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] While there he served in Harvard's Reserve Officers' Training Corps Field Artillery Battalion.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] He graduated magna cum laude in 1924, and received his Bachelor of Science (S.B.) degree in electrical engineering.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] Birch went to work in the Engineering Department of the New York Telephone Company.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] He applied for and received an American Field Service Fellowship in 1926, which he used to travel to Strasbourg, and study at the University of Strasbourg's Institut de Physique under the tutelage of Pierre Weiss.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] There, he wrote or co-wrote four papers, in French, on topics such as the paramagnetic properties of potassium cyanide, and the magnetic moment of Cu++ ions.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] On returning to the United States in 1928, Birch went back to Harvard to pursue physics.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] He was awarded his Master of Arts (A.M.) degree in 1929, and then commenced work on his 1932 Doctor of Philosophy (Ph.D.) degree under the supervision of Percy Bridgman, who would receive the Nobel Prize for Physics in 1946.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] For his thesis, Birch measured the vapor-liquid critical point of mercury.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] He determined this as 1460±20 °C and 1640±50 kg/cm2, results he published in 1932 in the *Physical Review*.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] Around this time, there was an increased interest in geophysics at Harvard University, and Reginald Aldworth Daly established a Committee for Experimental Geology and Geophysics that included Bridgman, astronomer Harlow Shapley, geologists Louis Caryl Graton and D.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] William Zisman, another one of Bridgman's Ph.D. students, was hired as the committee's research associate, but, having little interest in the study of rocks, he resigned in 1932.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] The position was then offered to Birch, who had little interest or experience in geology either, but with the advent of the Great Depression, jobs were hard to find, and he accepted.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] On July 15, 1933, Birch married Barbara Channing, a Bryn Mawr College alumna, and a collateral descendant of the theologian William Ellery Channing.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] They had three children: Anne Campaspe, Francis (Frank) Sylvanus and Mary Narcissa.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] Frank later became a professor of geophysics at the University of New Hampshire.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] In 1942, during World War II, Birch took a leave of absence from Harvard, in order to work at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology Radiation Laboratory, which was developing radar.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] He worked on the proximity fuze, a radar-triggered fuze that would explode a shell in the proximity of a target.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] The following year he accepted a commission in the United States Navy as a lieutenant commander, and was posted to the Bureau of Ships in Washington, D.C.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] Later that year he was assigned to the Manhattan Project, and moved with his family to Los Alamos, New Mexico.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] There he joined the Los Alamos Laboratory's Ordnance (O) Division, which was under the command of another Naval officer, Captain William S.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] Initially the goal of the O Division was to design a gun-type nuclear weapon known as Thin Man.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] This proved to be impractical due to contamination of the reactor-bred plutonium with plutonium-240, and in February 1944, the Division switched its attention to the development of the Little Boy, a smaller device using uranium-235.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] Birch used unenriched uranium to create scale models and later full-scale mock-ups of the device.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] Birch supervised the manufacture of the Little Boy, and went to Tinian to supervise its assembly and loading it onto *Enola Gay*, the Boeing B-29 Superfortress tasked with dropping the bomb.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] He devised the 'double plug' system that allowed for actually arming the bomb after *Enola Gay* took off so that if it crashed, there would not be a nuclear explosion.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] Birch was promoted to commander and released from the Navy in 1945.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] Birch returned to Harvard after the war ended, having been promoted to associate professor of geology in 1943 while he was away.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] He would remain at Harvard for the rest of his career, becoming a professor in 1946, and Sturgis Hooper Professor of Geology in 1949, and professor emeritus in 1974.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] Professor Birch published over 100 papers.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] He served as president of The Geological Society of America in 1964 and was awarded their Penrose Medal in 1969.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] In 1947, he adapted the isothermal Murnaghan equation of state, which had been developed for infinitesimal strain, for Eulerian finite strain, developing what is now known as the Birch-Murnaghan equation of state.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] His conclusions are still accepted as correct today.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] This relationship became known as Birch's law.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] Birch was elected to the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1942, the National Academy of Sciences in 1950, the American Philosophical Society in 1955, and served as the president of the Geological Society of America in 1963 and 1964.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] He received numerous honors in his career, including the Geological Society of America's Arthur L.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] Since 1992, the American Geophysical Union's Tectonophysics section has sponsored a Francis Birch Lecture, given at its annual meeting by a noted researcher in this field.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] Birch died of prostate cancer at his home in Cambridge, Massachusetts, on January 30, 1992.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] He was survived by wife Barbara, his three children and his three brothers.
[src:francis-birch-geophysicist/francis-birch-geophysicist] His papers are in the Harvard University Archives.
